macOS has two major “Library”

/Library/ – system-wide
~/Library/ – user-specific


ls /var/db/diagnostics/


log show log show --info --debug --last 1h 
log show --predicate 'process == "ssh"' --last 24h


Persistence and startup items live here: 

/Library/LaunchDaemons/ 
/Library/LaunchAgents/
~/Library/LaunchAgents/




Application and system configuration lives here too:

/Library/Preferences/ 
/Library/Logs/ 
/Library/Extensions/ (kernel extensions, now heavily restricted) 
/Library/Application Support/



The metadata database lives in: 

/. Spotlight-V100/ 
/VolumeName/.Spotlight-V100/



Tools like mdls and mdfind let you query the index: 

mdls /Users/user/Documents/report.pdf 
mdfind "kMDItemFSName == 'payload.sh'"




FSEvents is a real-time file activity tracker. It logs changes to folders and files at the directory level, including: 
●     file creation 
●     file deletion 
●     renames 
●     moves 
●     permission changes 
These logs live at: 
/. fseventsd/ 
/VolumeName/.fseventsd/



stat -x <file> 
This gives a detailed breakdown of every timestamp macOS tracks. It’s incredibly helpful when building a timeline or spotting manipulation attempts.




Apple stores configurations, preferences, application states, and system behaviors inside .plist files located in: 
●     /Library/Preferences/ 
●     /Library/LaunchDaemons/ 
●     /Library/LaunchAgents/ 
●     ~/Library/Preferences/ 
●     ~/Library/LaunchAgents/


To view binary plists: 
plutil -p <file> 
Or convert them: 
plutil -convert xml1 <file>






